reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 20, 2023
reviews.reviewText: Coming from 1050TI. The boost in performance can be noticed immediately.MSI made a great job with the looks of this model, the back plate is nice, only lacking a bit of rgb maybe in the logo for that +5fps LUL.It's a plus that AMD is taking care of this gen of GPUs on the drivers side. Tested the preview drivers and can say that AFMF helps a lot with fluidity on those poorly optimized games (yes, I'm looking at you, Escape from Tarkov). Got this on a nice deal around $190 before taxes 1yr ago, feeling it was worth every penny!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on May 20, 2022
reviews.reviewText: Pros: It was readily available when I wanted to upgrade my 1050ti. It doubles performance on every game I have (except GTA IV it does worse for some reason). Fans are off most of the time unless I’m playing a newer game maxed out.Cons: It’s kind of loud when under heavy load and the fans kick into high gear.I paired this with a Ryzen 5 5600g and 32gb 3200mhz ram. Overall I just decided to build my first pc at a time when the graphics card market is in shambles, so I can’t complain too much about price because idk how prices used to be. But for the $60 above msrp I paid it’s an amazing 1080p60 max settings card. I came from only having consoles for almost 20 years, and I play mostly rpgs or racing games so a locked 60fps isn’t a deal breaker. DOOM, BL3, Sekiro, Far Cry 4, MGSV, Forza Horizon 4 and 5 all run max graphics with no stutters or lag.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 2, 2023
reviews.reviewText: I got this card for $227 back in December 2022 and it was the absolute perfect time to buy it. It’s performance is comparable to an RTX 3060 and they both trade blows. FSR 2.0 works great and I’ve been getting well over 80 FPS in games like Cyberpunk 2077, Red Dead Redemption 2, and Modern Warfare 2 all on ultra settings. One complaint I have though is the noise. It can be fixed with a fan curve but it’s miles better than my XFX RX 590 which was a total nightmare. Overall, extremely good card and I can’t really complain considering the price I got it at. 👍-Just one thing though: AMD Radeon Software, I can’t turn the power limit over zero or see my clock speeds and temps in Unigine Benchmark (Heaven and Superposition). I also can’t control the GPU fans in third party software like FanControl. IF YOU HAVE A FIX FOR THE POWER LIMIT OR IF THAT’S JUST HOW THE GPU IS BUILT, TELL ME.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on May 11, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Damn good in this market
reviews.reviewText: It's a damn good card for the price, when you think about the times we are coming out of.I was tired of gaming on an iGPU, and for 320 bucks I just bit the bullet. It serves the 1080p purpose real well, and even 1440p 60fps is achievable if you pull those ultra settings down a notch.IMPORTANT: If you're an overclocker, don't get this MSI model. It's wattage is limited to the stock 100 watts, unlike most other 6600s in the market. I don't mind, and if you aren't an overclocking kinda guy, you really shouldn't care too much either. It will still let you undervolt and overclock it, you just won't be able to make it pull more power, which will limit how much you can push it.
